<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[578,1854,1334,1555]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
More distant from the two following species than they from each other, larger, with more robust 
<emphasis box="[774,850,1381,1408]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">cerci</emphasis>
, paired black spots on S2-7 and generally much more blue on the abdomen. It has a smaller range confined to the Himalayas in northern and eastern India and Bhutan, with a surely erroneous record from Taiwan (
<bibRefCitation author="Dow, R. A." box="[1558,1723,1477,1504]" journalOrPublisher="The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2014.3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" publicationUrl="www.iucnredlist.org" refId="ref3945" refString="Dow, R. A. 2009. Indolestes cyaneus. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2014.3. &lt;www. iucnredlist. org&gt;. Downloaded on 15 II 2015." title="Indolestes cyaneus" type="url" year="2009">Dow 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Joshi, S. &amp; K. Kunte" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Threatened Taxa" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="6458 - 6472" part="6" refId="ref4117" refString="Joshi, S. &amp; K. Kunte. 2014. Dragonflies and damselflies (Insecta: Odonata) of Nagaland, with an addition to the Indian odonate fauna. Journal of Threatened Taxa 6: 6458 - 6472." title="Dragonflies and damselflies (Insecta: Odonata) of Nagaland, with an addition to the Indian odonate fauna" type="journal article" year="2014">Joshi &amp; Kunte 2014</bibRefCitation>
